I"û<p>While a <em>partition</em> of a set is a grouping of its elements into non-empty subsets in such a way that every element is included in exactly one subset, a relation on a set \(S\) is a condition that determines if \(a \sim b\) is true.</p>

<p><strong>Example 1</strong>
Let \(S = \{0, 1, 2, 3, 4\}\) a relation \(\sim\) on \(S\) is the rule â€œ\(a\) and \(b\) have the same remainder when divided by 3 .â€  To decide which elements are make this statement true, we can build a chart:</p>

