<p><label for="partmod3" class="margin-toggle">âŠ•</label>
<input type="checkbox" id="partmod3" class="margin-toggle" />
<span class="marginnote"><img class="fullwidth" src="/ISPeL-content-machine-learning/assets/img/partition-mod-3.svg" alt="The set $$\{0, 1, 2, 3, 4\}$$ is partitioned by a set of three sets $$\{0, 3\}$$, $$\{1, 4\}$$ and $$\{2\}$$." /><br />
    The set \(\{0, 1, 2, 3, 4\}\) is partitioned by a set of three sets \(\{0, 3\}\), \(\{1, 4\}\) and \(\{2\}\).
</span>
<!--- <img src="../../../../assets/img/set-union.svg" alt="Drawing" style="width: 333px;" align="center;"> ---></p>

<p>A relation \(\sim\) on a set \(S\) is an <strong>equivalence relation</strong> if:</p>

<ol>
  <li>the relation is <em>reflexive</em>, for all \(x\) in \(S,\) the statement â€œ\(x \sim x\)â€ is true; and</li>
  <li>the relation is <em>symmetric</em>, that is for all \(x\) and \(y\) in \(S\) the statement â€œ\(x \sim y \rightarrow y \sim x\);â€ and</li>
  <li>the relation is <em>transitive</em>, for all \(x, y\) and \(z\) in \(S\) the statement â€œIf \(x \sim y\) and \(y \sim x\) then \(x \sim z.\)â€</li>
</ol>

<p>Every <em>equivalence relation</em> on a set defines a partition of the set, and every partition defines an equivalence relation. Our example of the partition of the set \(\{0, 1, 2, 3, 4\}\) is generated by
the relation \(x \sim y\) if and only if \(\lfloor \frac{x}{3}\rfloor = \lfloor \frac{y}{3}\rfloor.\)</p>

